Description: SynerG, under the umbrella of Action Greensboro.
Full Description: synerG, under the umbrella of Action Greensboro, is an active organization of young adults who lead initiatives with the mission to attract, engage and connect young professionals to Greensboro, North Carolina. Through our projects, synerG promotes social and professional networking, leadership opportunities and serves as a clearinghouse for information for young adults in the 21-39 year-old age demographic. synerG values the creation of opportunities and atmospheres that promote connectedness, diversity/inclusiveness and accessibility.  In 2001, Action Greensboro commissioned the McKinsey Report on the state of economic growth in Greensboro. One strong finding was that Greensboro had been seeing a decline in numbers of 18- to 34-year-olds in the past decade. During the same time period, Raleigh and Charlotte had been able to attract young people from outside their county lines, increasing their absolute number of young residents and bucking the national trend toward an aging population. With this challenge, Action Greensboro created synerG.  Since 2001, synerG has evolved from developing projects like the installation of WIFI on South Elm Street and in Center City Park to program based initiatives with the goal of advancing leadership opportunities, voice, and quality of life for all young professionals in the Greensboro community.

Description: Quantified Self serves its user community by conducting meetings, forums, web content and services, and a guide to self-tracking tools.
Headquarters Regions: Greater San Diego Area, West Coast, Western US
Full Description: The Quantified Self is a movement to incorporate technology into data acquisition on aspects of a person's daily life in terms of inputs (e.g. food consumed, quality of surrounding air), states (e.g. mood, arousal, blood oxygen levels), and performance (mental and physical). Such self-monitoring and self-sensing, which combines wearable sensors (EEG, ECG, video, etc.) and wearable computing, is also known as lifelogging or sousveillance. Other names for using self-tracking data to improve daily functioning are “self-tracking”, "auto-analytics", “body hacking” and “self-quantifying”. The movement was started under the name "Quantified Self" by Wired Magazine editors Gary Wolf and Kevin Kelly in 2007 as "a collaboration of users and tool makers who share an interest in self knowledge through self-tracking". In 2010, Wolf spoke about the movement at TED, and in May 2011 the first international conference was held in Mountain View, California. Today the global community has over [a hundred groups in 31 countries around the world](http://quantifiedself.meetup.com).
Industry Groups: Data and Analytics, Design, Hardware, Information Technology, Software

App Ed Review is a full-fledged resource for teachers.
Full Description: App Ed Review was born in the spring 2012 semester, when Dr. Todd Cherner was teaching a graduate-level literacy class at Coastal Carolina University. As part of that class, Todd set aside time for “app-etizers” that were mini-lessons about apps. Because the school district where the majority of his students worked provided each of them an iPad to use in their classroom, Todd’s students were very interested in these mini-lessons. Then, during one of these app-etizers, a student asked him, “What makes an app good to use in the classroom?” Although Todd had been using apps as part of his teaching for two years at this point, he had never considered the worth of an app. In response, Todd investigated if there was a research-based app evaluation rubric and he found that a comprehensive one had yet to be developed. At this point, Todd met with Dr. Corey Lee and discussed how they could create such a rubric.

Description: STONEHENGE GARDENS, LLC. the Company, intends to create and construct a tourist attraction and event venue in Las Vegas, Nevada.
Full Description: STONEHENGE GARDENS, LLC. the Company, intends to create and construct a tourist attraction and event venue in Las Vegas, Nevada. The project will have the full scale complete recreation of the ancient megalithic monument in Southern England known worldwide as Stonehenge.  The Stonehenge Project will result the creation of a major tourist attraction and event venue for weddings, private parties and corporate events with facilities for catering and seating in a thirty-five hundred square foot air conditioned tent facility.  Stonehenge Gardens has an available target market of an estimated 40 million tourists that visit Las Vegas every year as well as its local Clark County population of over 2 million for additional revenues from visitation and event venue use. Stonehenge Gardens will be strategically located on 2.5 acres just 3 miles south of the Mandalay Bay on the Las Vegas strip with 770 feet of frontage on Interstate 15. Interstate 15 is the major access road from Southern California to the south, Utah to the north, and Colorado and New Mexico to the east. Intrastate 15 has a traffic count of 42,500 cars a day which is 42% of the all of the traffic coming into Las Vegas per day. The property zoning permits up to a 100 linier foot illuminated double sided pylon sign to be built on the highway frontage.  57% of all visitors to Las Vegas travel by car, bus, RV, or truck. Another 43% of visitors arrive by air during approach the site which is located about 3.5 miles from the two main runways 19 L, 19 R of McCarran Airport will be certainly visible and it is unknown what if anything can be attributed to this proximity. The close proximity to the Las Vegas strip insures the easy access to venue. A short cab ride will allow for easy access and an affordable ride to and from Stonehenge Gardens for those who arrive by air or bus.
Industry Groups: Events, Media and Entertainment, Travel and Tourism
